6 December 1124":"16 December 1124","1120":"1120","1065":"1065","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1086":"1086","1095":"1095","9 March 1100":"9 March 1100","1004":"1004","1124":"1124","Abt 1100":"about 1100","1100":"1100","1144":"1144","about 1086":"about 1086","Wettin, Saalkreis, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany":"Wettin, Saalkreis, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany","Naumburg, Saxony, Germany":"Naumburg, Saxony, Germany","Meissen, Dresden, Saxony, Germany":"Meißen, Saxony, Germany","Wettin, Saalekreis, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany":"Wettin, Saalkreis, Saxony-Anhalt, Germany","Meissen, Mark Meissen, Herzogtum Sachsen, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Meißen, Meißen, Saxony, Germany","Palestine":"Palestine","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Wettin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Johan, Tor.","Swedish: ornamental or habitational name formed with an altered form of the (placename) element <i>väst</i> ‘west’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Westen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Westen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shosh, Shoshana.  German Ulrich.","German, Dutch, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German, Middle Low German, Middle Dutch <i>westen</i>, German <i>Westen</i> ‘west’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived to the west of a settlement, or a habitational name for one who had migrated from further west. The Jewish name may also be of ornamental origin.","Swedish (mainly <b>Westén</b>): ornamental or habitational name formed with an altered form of the (placename) element <i>väst</i> ‘west’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-én</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Westin  ."]}]},{"name":"Dedo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dedo IV von Wettin was born abou